Introducing dates, times
and time series

Date and time types and formats

  • Dates and times can be represented in different ways

  • There are lots of different date and time formats

  • A date-time is a data type that includes a date and a time

  • It can be frustrating getting your times into the right format

  • I’ll use R packages lubridate and base

Time series data

  • Events occurring sequentially through time can be thought of as time series

  • These could be weather measurements, purchases, football match outcomes, even locations in space

In this lecture

  • We will first go through different types of time and date classes

  • Then we will do some visualisation and exploration of time series

Dates, times and date-times

Battle of the libraries: base vs lubridate

  • in base R dates and date-times have a special class called posixCT
# date-time including time zone
Sys.time()
## [1] "2021-03-30 14:06:31 SAST"
# date in current time zone
Sys.Date()
## [1] "2021-03-30"

Dates, times and date-times

Battle of the libraries: base vs lubridate

  • lubridate is a tidyverse package
  • You can do what we did above using lubridate
# date-time including time zone
now()  # lubridate
## [1] "2021-03-30 14:06:31 SAST"
# date in current time zone
today()  # lubridate
## [1] "2021-03-30"

Reading in date information

  • This can be harder than it should be, especially when using tab- or comma-delimited formats
wind_data <- read.csv("data/wind_direction.csv")
head(wind_data, n = 3)
##    Location       Date Wind_direction_degrees
## 1 Cape Town 06/02/2020                    150
## 2 Cape Town 07/02/2020                    136
## 3 Cape Town 08/02/2020                    162
class(wind_data$Date)
## [1] "factor"

Changing the date format with base

  • As you can see, R thinks the date column is a factor
  • In base R you often need to specify the “Unix Epoch”
    1970-01-01 in the origin argument
my_base_date <- as.Date(as.character(wind_data$Date), 
                        tryFormats = c("%d-%m-%Y", "%d/%m/%Y"), 
                        origin="1970-01-01")
head(my_base_date, n=4) 
## [1] "2020-02-06" "2020-02-07" "2020-02-08" "2020-02-09"
class(my_base_date)
## [1] "Date"

Changing the date format with lubridate

  • lubridate syntax is intuitive and compact
class(wind_data$Date)
## [1] "factor"
my_lbdt_date <- dmy(as.character(wind_data$Date))
head(my_lbdt_date, n = 4)
## [1] "2020-02-06" "2020-02-07" "2020-02-08" "2020-02-09"
class(my_lbdt_date)
## [1] "Date"

Pitfalls

  • The as.character bit is important!
as.Date(wind_data$Date, 
        format="%Y-%m-%d", tz="SAST", 
        origin="1970-01-01")
## [1] NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
as.Date(as.character(wind_data$Date), 
        format="%d/%m/%Y", tz="SAST", 
        origin="1970-01-01")
## [1] "2020-02-06" "2020-02-07" "2020-02-08" "2020-02-09"
"2020-02-10"
## [6] "2020-02-11" "2020-02-12"

Pitfalls

  • If you tell R the object contains times it will make them up
my_fake_dt <- as.POSIXct(my_lbdt_date, format = "%Y-%m-%d", tz = "SAST", 
    origin = "1970-01-01 00:00:00")
head(my_fake_dt, n = 4)
## [1] "2020-02-06 02:00:00 SAST" "2020-02-07 02:00:00 SAST"
## [3] "2020-02-08 02:00:00 SAST" "2020-02-09 02:00:00 SAST"

Pitfalls

  • You can’t add a timezone to a date
  • Even if you do add it, like we did, it won’t show up
my_base_date <- as.Date(as.character(wind_data$Date), 
                        tryFormats = c("%d-%m-%Y", "%d/%m/%Y"), 
                        origin="1970-01-01",tz="SAST")
head(my_base_date, n=4) 
## [1] "2020-02-06" "2020-02-07" "2020-02-08" "2020-02-09"

Pitfalls

  • Format mistakes
  • The format argument must match the current format of the date
as.Date(as.character(wind_data$Date), format = "%Y-%m-%d", tz = "SAST", 
    origin = "1970-01-01")
## [1] NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
as.Date(as.character(wind_data$Date), format = "%Y/%m/%d", tz = "SAST", 
    origin = "1970-01-01")
## [1] "0006-02-20" "0007-02-20" "0008-02-20"

Many format options…

ymd("2020-01-31")
## [1] "2020-01-31"
mdy("January 31st, 2020")
## [1] "2020-01-31"
dmy("31-Jan-2020")
## [1] "2020-01-31"
ymd(20200131)
## [1] "2020-01-31"

Date-times can also have lots of formats

ymd_hms("2020-01-31 14:09:21")
## [1] "2020-01-31 14:09:21 UTC"
mdy_hm("01/31/2020 06:09")
## [1] "2020-01-31 06:09:00 UTC"
mdy_h("01/31/2020 06")
## [1] "2020-01-31 06:00:00 UTC"

Time zones

  • You can specify a time zone up-front
ymd_hms("2020-01-31 14:09:21", tz = "Africa/Johannesburg")
## [1] "2020-01-31 14:09:21 SAST"
  • Or add it later
mytime <- ymd_hms("2020-01-31 14:09:21")
with_tz(mytime, tzone = "Africa/Johannesburg")
## [1] "2020-01-31 16:09:21 SAST"

Once you have a date, time or
date-time object

  • You can extract elements from it, like the date
womensday <- ymd_hms("2020-08-09-12-30-30", tz = "GMT")
womensday
## [1] "2020-08-09 12:30:30 GMT"
date(womensday)
## [1] "2020-08-09"
month(womensday)
## [1] 8
# Is it a leap year?
leap_year(womensday)
## [1] TRUE

Once you have a date, time or
date-time object

  • Or elements of the time
hour(womensday)
## [1] 12
minute(womensday)
## [1] 30
second(womensday)
## [1] 30

Once you have a date, time or
date-time object

  • Or elements of the calendar date
mday(womensday)
## [1] 9
wday(womensday, label = TRUE)
## [1] Sun
## Levels: Sun < Mon < Tue < Wed < Thu < Fri < Sat
yday(womensday)
## [1] 222

You can also create datetimes
from their components

temp_data <- read.csv("data/temperature.csv")
head(temp_data, n = 3)
##    Location Temperature Day Month Year Hour Minute Second
## 1 Cape Town        20.1   6     2 2020    8     30     41
## 2 Cape Town        22.9   6     2 2020    9     10      2
## 3 Cape Town        23.6   6     2 2020    9     49     23

You can also create datetimes
from their components

temp_data %>% select(Year, Month, Day, Hour, Minute, Second) %>% 
    mutate(DateTime = make_datetime(Year, Month, Day, Hour, Minute, 
        Second))
##   Year Month Day Hour Minute Second            DateTime
## 1 2020     2   6    8     30     41 2020-02-06 08:30:41
## 2 2020     2   6    9     10      2 2020-02-06 09:10:02
## 3 2020     2   6    9     49     23 2020-02-06 09:49:23
## 4 2020     2   6   10     28     44 2020-02-06 10:28:44
## 5 2020     2   6   11      8      5 2020-02-06 11:08:05
## 6 2020     2   6   11     47     26 2020-02-06 11:47:26
## 7 2020     2   6   12     26     47 2020-02-06 12:26:47

Rounding dates

  • Sometimes you might want to round a date
floor_date(now(), unit = "minutes")
## [1] "2021-03-30 14:06:00 SAST"
ceiling_date(now(), unit = "minutes")
## [1] "2021-03-30 14:07:00 SAST"

Time spans

  • Durations: exact number of seconds between events

  • Periods: track clock time between events in human units like weeks and months

  • Intervals: have a start and an end point

Durations

  • Durations: a time span in exact number of seconds
  • Subtracting two dates can give confusing results
  • Durations only measure time in seconds

How old is Kanye West?

kw_age <- today() - ymd(19770608)
kw_age
## Time difference of 16001 days
as.duration(kw_age)
## [1] "1382486400s (~43.81 years)"

Durations

How old will Kanye West be next week?

kw_age + dweeks(1)
## Time difference of 1383091200 secs
as.duration(kw_age + dweeks(1))
## [1] "1383091200s (~43.83 years)"

Periods

  • Periods: accurately track clock time despite human time constructs like leap seconds, leap years and daylight savings
months(8) + days(12) + seconds(3)
## [1] "8m 12d 0H 0M 3S"
ymd("2020-01-01") + dyears(1)
## [1] "2020-12-31 06:00:00 UTC"
# > [1] '2016-12-31 06:00:00 UTC'
ymd("2020-01-01") + years(1)
## [1] "2021-01-01"
# > [1] '2017-01-01'

Intervals

  • Intervals: have a start and an end point
# Create an interval in time
lunch <- paste(as.character(today()), "12-30-05")
lunchtime <- ymd_hms(lunch, tz = "Africa/Johannesburg")
lunchtime
## [1] "2021-03-30 12:30:05 SAST"
time_since_lunch <- lubridate::interval(lunchtime, now())
time_since_lunch
## [1] 2021-03-30 12:30:05 SAST--2021-03-30 14:06:32 SAST
as.duration(time_since_lunch)
## [1] "5787.50559997559s (~1.61 hours)"

Intervals

  • Intervals are made up of two dates
# Access the start of an interval
start <- int_start(time_since_lunch)
start
## [1] "2021-03-30 12:30:05 SAST"
# Access the end point of an interval
end <- int_end(time_since_lunch)
end
## [1] "2021-03-30 14:06:32 SAST"

Explorating time series through visualisation

  • Packages tsibble, feasts, brolgar, dygraphs
  • Datasets:
    • dolphin sightings at Cape Vidal, KZN
    • wage data from the brolgar package
    • purchase data from Kaggle
  • What is a time series?
    • a list of numbers of interest, indexed by the times those numbers were recorded
    • there is a special type of dataframe in R for time series, a tsibble

Dolphin sightings

  • Hourly number of dolphin sightings

Dolphin sightings

  • Weekly number of dolphin sightings
  • We only keep date to help us with plotting
weekly_counts <- hourly_counts %>% mutate(week = week(datetime)) %>% 
    group_by(week, location) %>% summarise(sum_counts = sum(dolphin_counts), 
    sum_effort = sum(effort), mean_sight = mean(sightability), 
    date = mean(datetime))
head(weekly_counts, n = 3)
## # A tibble: 3 x 6
## # Groups: week [2]
## week location sum_counts sum_effort mean_sight date
## <dbl> <chr> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dttm>
## 1 22 Cape Vidal 41 97 3.06 1990-06-03 09:22:30
## 2 22 Richards Bay 18 97 3.06 1990-06-03 09:22:30
## 3 23 Cape Vidal 88 202 3.56 1990-06-07 23:35:17

From dataframe to tsibble

weekly_counts <- as_tsibble(x = weekly_counts, key = location, 
    index = week, regular = TRUE)
head(weekly_counts)
## # A tsibble: 6 x 6 [1]
## # Key: location [1]
## # Groups: @ week [6]
## week location sum_counts sum_effort mean_sight date
## <dbl> <chr> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dttm>
## 1 22 Cape Vidal 41 97 3.06 1990-06-03 09:22:30
## 2 23 Cape Vidal 88 202 3.56 1990-06-07 23:35:17
## 3 24 Cape Vidal 180 355 3.66 1990-06-15 05:03:52
## 4 25 Cape Vidal 108 213 3.31 1990-06-20 10:56:40
## 5 26 Cape Vidal 95 201 2.97 1990-06-26 10:56:15
## 6 27 Cape Vidal 164 378 3.45 1990-07-07 05:00:00

Plotting a time series

weekly_counts %>% ggplot(aes(x = date, y = sum_counts)) + geom_line() + 
    ylab("Total weekly sightings") + xlab("Month") + facet_grid(~location)

Seasonal decomposition

sdecomp <- weekly_counts %>% model(STL(sum_counts ~ trend())) %>% 
    components()

autoplot(sdecomp) + xlab("Week")

Individuals through time with brolgar

  • As you can see it’s a tsibble and it was created like this
wages <- as_tsibble(x = wages,
                    key = id,
                    index = xp,
                    regular = FALSE)

Individuals through time with brolgar

  • Really nice functionality for exploring datasets composed of time series from many individuals or groupings, e.g.,

    • individual humans or animals
    • individual locations
    • individual companies
    • individual sports teams
    • …

Sample a handful of time series

wages %>%
  sample_n_keys(size = 5) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = xp, y = ln_wages, group = id)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  labs(y="Log(wage)", x="Experience (number of years)")

Sample a handful of time series

ggplot(wages,
       aes(x = xp, y = ln_wages, group = id)) +
       geom_line() + facet_sample(n_per_facet = 3, n_facets = 6) +
  labs(y="Log(wage)", x="Experience (number of years)")

Interactive time series plots

weekly_counts %>% dplyr::select(location, week, sum_counts) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = location, values_from = sum_counts) %>% 
  dygraph() %>% dyOptions(stackedGraph = FALSE) %>%
  dyRangeSelector(height = 20)

weekly_counts %>% dplyr::select(location, week, sum_counts) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = location, values_from = sum_counts) %>% 
  dygraph() %>% dyOptions(stackedGraph = TRUE) %>%
  dyRangeSelector(height = 20)
